  text: |-
    In the year Xinsi of the Zhizheng era, at fourteen years old, I went to take the examination at the National Academy. Standing in the courtyard, I beheld the Master—robed and holding his tablet of office, sitting upright with such dignity that he seemed like Mount Tai itself, a towering peak. All the scholars held their breath, not daring to whisper.

    Once I became his student, attending his lectures, I found him speaking with gentle words and soft countenance, illuminating the laws of our nation, nurturing talent with tireless encouragement. Yet he sighed with melancholy, lamenting how the customs of our age grow ever more debased.

    At home, he concerned himself little with worldly gain. Around him lay only his qin and books, simple and serene. He planted pines upon the eastern slope and lotuses in the southern pond. Each year when the peonies bloomed in his garden, he would prepare wine and feast, summoning his students to offer longevity to his lady wife. Her brothers and descendants would gather in perfect harmony—such was the depth of his filial piety and fraternal love that it moved heaven and earth itself. His lady lived to ninety-one years, a life of true abundance.

    In the third month of the year Bingshen, his lady passed away from illness. She was buried beside the tomb of his father, the late Minister of Integrity. He remained there to complete the mourning rites. Though the Master had long been troubled by illness, making walking difficult, each morning and evening he would personally sweep and tend the grave, never neglecting this duty. In our land, it is common for others to maintain the tombs of their parents, even freeing servants from their obligations. Yet the Master could not bear to neglect his duty to his own blood. He performed all tasks himself—something unknown among the great ministers of recent times.

    The Master's name was Kim Gwang-sik, with the courtesy name Ja-yeo and the sobriquet Pine Hall Recluse. He was of Gwangju, descended from the Chamberlain Kim Gil, who served our Great Founder with distinction. Through the generations, his line produced the General Gwang-seo, the Three Ministers Inspector Gyeong-ryang, the General of the Realm Su-won, and others of renown. The Inspector met his end defending Yeong-gwang against the Three Patrols who refused submission.

    The Inspector married a daughter of the National Academy Director Go Yeong-jung. She lived to one hundred and two years. In her dreams, she beheld a bright star descending into her embrace, and she bore the Bright Heart Master, Minister of Integrity Tai-hyeon. He served as counselor to four reigns, compiling the literary works of our kingdom into the Haedong Anthology, which circulated widely. When he presided over the examinations at the National Academy, the scholars he selected became renowned throughout the land—among them the meticulous Ahn of Bamboo Valley and the eccentric Choe stand out as the finest.

    The Minister first married a daughter of the General Kim Ui, and fathered the first son, Gwang-sik, who rose to the rank of Minister of Selection. His second wife, descended from the Prince Hyo-eun and daughter of the Attendant Lord Jeong Dan, bore three sons and two daughters. The eldest, Gwang-cheol, achieved high office at the Royal Chancellery; the second was our Master; and the third, Gwang-ro, also passed the examinations with distinction. The daughters married well—the eldest to the Literary Official Ahn Mok, and the second to the Lord of Milyang Park Yun-mun.

    When all three brothers achieved office, the lady received official stipend throughout her life. Four sons of Park and three grandsons of Ahn also rose through examination—a source of great envy among their contemporaries.

    The Master was born in the first month on an auspicious day of the year Jiayuan, already surpassing two feet in height, a sign of his extraordinary nature. His parents cherished him greatly. After his coming of age, he passed the examination in the year Guichou of the Huangqing era. His examiner, the First Scholar Gwon Jung-seung, recognized his mastery of ritual and treated him generously, appointing him to the Academy.

    In the year Gengwu of Zhishun, he followed King Chung-hye to the capital, where his merit was recognized with appointment as Chamberlain's Secretary, later promoted to the Ministry of Works. In the year Jimao of Later Zhiyuan, when King Chung-hye faced near deposition by Cao Di but miraculously escaped, the King's faction sought to consolidate power at court. When the King departed for the capital, the Master declared, "Our sovereign is in peril. How can I alone seek safety?" He followed the King, and through heaven's grace, the King's authority was restored and he returned home in the autumn of the year Gengchen.

    The Master ascended through ranks—Military Affairs Prefect, Academy Director, Minister of the Three Departments, Judge of the National Archive—holding concurrent posts in the Archives and as Drafter of Royal Edicts. The following autumn, presiding over the Academy examinations, he selected ninety-nine scholars, among them the celebrated Seong Sa-dal, earning praise for discerning talent.

    King Chung-hye, growing wary of the Master's severity, and surrounded by those who resented him, found no grounds for reproach until he said, "Kim is a man of quiet disposition; he has no ambition for office." The King believed this, and the Master's position was stripped away. Lesser men then grew bold.

    In the winter of the year Gyemi, the calamity of Ak-yang occurred. In the year Gapcsin, when King Chung-mok ascended the throne, the Master was called forth as Right Deputy Prime Minister, later promoted to Minister of State. Powerful ministers, resenting his refusal to flatter them, had him appointed Minister of Maps—yet the King soon regretted this, elevating him instead to Royal Chancellor with oversight of examinations, then further to Minister of Justice.

    When King Chung-jeong ascended in the year Gichwi, he opened the Royal Lectures and made the Master his teacher. Though the Master demurred, he was appointed Counselor, then Scholar-Official, Great Master of the Archives, and Court Guardian, continuing to oversee the examinations. When promoted to Minister of the Right, he advised the King: "Selection of civil officials is the Ministry of Personnel's duty; selection of military officials belongs to the Ministry of War. That the Political Secretariat oversees both is an innovation of ambitious ministers, not the proper law. If Your Highness will hear my counsel, restoration to the ancient way would be most fitting." The King agreed, yet entrusted him to oversee both selections, requiring his personal oversight.

    When King Hyeon ascended in the tenth month of the year Sinmyo, the Master withdrew from the world, devoting himself to caring for his lady wife with perfect propriety morning and evening. When his mourning rites concluded, the Minister Hongyangpa and other great officials came to offer condolences. The Master wept, saying, "At sixty-three, when I first came to dwell here in seclusion, I constantly feared I would predecease my mother, bringing shame upon my clan. That I have lived to this day is the blessing of my departed parents." All present wept with him in admiration.

    After the mourning period, he established an ancestral altar in the northern corner of his hall, weeping without cease at each rite. Confined by chronic illness, he did not venture beyond his gate. When King Hyeon learned of his virtuous withdrawal, he sent an emissary with words: "I have long wished to speak with you. Would you grant this old man the honor of an audience?" The Master, in reverent distress, was supported by his sons to the palace. The King observed, "Your appearance shows little decline. What ailment confines you so?" He sighed with deep concern for a long while, then commanded that the Master's village be marked with a gate inscribed "Lane of the Filial Son" and that several households be freed from taxation to honor him.

    In the eleventh month of the year Sinchuk, fleeing the Red Turbans, the Master journeyed to Gochang County, where he remained. In the third month of the year Gyemyo, he felt a slight indisposition, yet his movements and speech showed no alteration. On the evening of the fourteenth day, he said to his wife, "I am seventy years old. What regret can death bring? It is the ancient rite that a man should not expire in a woman's care. Please withdraw with the servants." He instructed them: "Speak not loudly, nor utter hurried words to disturb me." Shortly after, his breath ceased—such was the depth of his lifelong cultivation.

    His sons and sons-in-law bore his coffin back to the capital and buried him beneath the family tomb at Deoksu.

    The Master married the daughter of the Prime Minister Kim Seung-taek, the good and forthright. They had two children. His son, Heung-jo, was of bright and ambitious character, rising to the position of Minister of Military Affairs. He served with distinction as prefect of Suwon and Haeju, yet fell to the hand of the treacherous Choe—a death that men lament to this day. His daughter married the Magnanimous Official Park Mun-su, descended from Hyeokgeose, the ancient founder of Silla.

    The Minister's grandson by his son married a daughter of the Censor Shin Jung-jeon, bearing one daughter who wed the General Song Ui-beon. The son of Park had two sons: the elder, Chong, loved learning and cultivated noble aims, serving as Right Guard Protector-General; the younger, Pao, passed the examination and served as Keeper of Court Ceremony. There are numerous great-grandchildren, all yet young.

    The Guard, bearing his grandfather's record, came to me, Lee Saek of Hanssan, requesting an epitaph. He said, "You should compose this." Thus I received it and have set it down.

    Ah! The Master's virtue and his service were so manifest—surely his descendants should be many. Yet the Minister of Military Affairs left no heir. This is heaven's mystery, showing that heaven's preference differs from man's desire. How sorrowful! Yet there is solace: the Park line continues. Throughout history, scholars who have honored their maternal grandfather's memory are without number. Let the Park line strive on! Let them strive on!

    Thus I have composed this epitaph:

    *Upon the eastern slope*
    *The verdant pines stand tall—*
    *The dwelling of the noble man.*
    *The waters of the pond run full,*
    *The lotus fragrance floats clear—*
    *The virtue of the noble man.*

    *When he went forth to serve his king,*
    *His governance was just, his writings bright,*
    *He set our realm aright.*
    *When he returned to serve his parents,*
    *Each year more true, more deep,*
    *He transformed the people's ways.*

    *The Master's lofty influence*
    *Spreads wide across our eastern lands,*
    *An eternal model for all ages.*
    *I compose this epitaph*
    *Not from private affection,*
    *But as the impartial testimony of the historian's brush.
